 scholarly inquiry, and the involvement of art historians in wider debates about the cultural and political identity of the monarchy. The so-called Vienna School plays the central role in the study, but Rampley also examines the formation of art history elsewhere in Austria-Hungary. Located in the Habsburg imperial capital, Vienna art historians frequently became entangled in debates that were of importance to art historians elsewhere in the Empire, and Rampley pays particular attention to these areas of overlapping interest. He also analyzes the methodological innovations for which the Vienna School was well known. Rampley focuses most fully, however, on the larger political and ideological context of the practice of art history-particularly the way in which art-historical debates served as proxies for wider arguments over the political, social, and cultural life of the Habsburg Empire.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aArt and societyxHistoryx19th centuryxAustria. 0aArt and societyxHistoryx20th centuryxAustria. 0aArt and societyzAustriaxHistoryy19th century. 0aArt and societyzAustriaxHistoryy20th century. 0aArt historiansxAustria. 0aArt historianszAustria. 0aArtxHistoriographyxAustria. 0aArtxPolitical aspectsxHistoryx19th centuryxAustria. 0aArtxPolitical aspectsxHistoryx20th centuryxAustria. 0aArtxPolitical aspectszAustriaxHistoryy19th century. 0aArtxPolitical aspectszAustriaxHistoryy20th century. 0aArtzAustriaxHistoriography. 7aART / History / Modern (late 19th Century to 1945).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271062600423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271062600.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State Univ